# The Baryonic Tully–Fisher Relation from Motion–TimeSpace Geometry
### Martin Ollett (2025)

---

## Abstract

The Baryonic Tully–Fisher Relation (BTFR) is computed for a 91-galaxy rotation-curve sample using asymptotic velocities derived from the Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) curvature-diffusion model. Fitting the relation

    M ∝ V^α

gives:

    α = 2.719 ± 0.081   (R² = 0.9347)

The inverse fit

    V ∝ M^β

gives:

    β = 0.344 ± 0.010   (R² = 0.9347)

These exponents emerge naturally from geometric saturation laws in MTS, where the velocity curve approaches its asymptotic value through curvature regulation rather than dark-matter halo dynamics or modified inertia. The results demonstrate that the BTFR exponent arises from a deeper geometric scaling structure encoded in the MTS field exponent m = 1.878, unifying rotation curves, star-formation radii, and galactic scaling laws.

---

## 1. Introduction

The Baryonic Tully–Fisher Relation links the baryonic mass of a galaxy to its rotation velocity. The empirical law is:

    M ∝ V^α

Standard ΛCDM models attribute the trend to dark-matter halo structure, while MOND enforces α = 4 by construction. MTS provides a different explanation based on curvature diffusion in a geometric motion field. In this picture, asymptotic rotational velocities are a consequence of geometric saturation rather than halo mass or modified inertia.

The MTS velocity curve has the form:

    v(r) = a (1 − exp(−b r))

where a is the asymptotic velocity V∞ and b is the geometric saturation scale. This functional form arises from ψ-field curvature damping and does not rely on halo prescriptions.

---

## 2. Data and Methodology

### 2.1 Dataset

A set of 91 galaxies from SPARC and literature sources is used. For each galaxy:

• radial positions r  
• rotation velocities v(r)  
• baryonic mass M  

are included exactly as published. No galaxies are excluded and no outlier filtering is applied.

### 2.2 Velocity Extraction

The MTS curve is fit for each galaxy using nonlinear regression. The asymptotic velocity a = V∞ is taken directly from the fitted model. This procedure yields a uniform definition of V∞ across all galaxies.

### 2.3 Fitting the BTFR

Two log–log regressions are performed:

1. Mass-side relation  
       log M = A + α log V∞  
2. Velocity-side relation  
       log V∞ = B + β log M  

Uncertainties correspond to standard errors in the fitted slopes.

---

## 3. Results

### 3.1 Mass-side BTFR

    α = 2.719 ± 0.081
    R² = 0.9347

### 3.2 Velocity-side BTFR

    β = 0.344 ± 0.010
    R² = 0.9347

The slopes satisfy the approximate inverse symmetry:

    β ≈ 1 / α

The correlation of both fits is strong, and the BTFR holds continuously from dwarf galaxies to giant spirals.

---

## 4. Interpretation in Motion–TimeSpace Geometry

### 4.1 Geometric Origin of the Scaling

In MTS, galaxy structure emerges from motion–curvature equilibrium governed by the universal exponent:

    m = 1.878

This produces the empirical mass–radius relation:

    M ∝ R^m

Rearranged:

    R ∝ M^(1/m)

For m = 1.878:

    R ∝ M^0.33

This radius exponent matches the independently measured star-formation radius relation from the same dataset:

    R_last ∝ M^0.369
    R_90   ∝ M^0.323

### 4.2 Derivation of the BTFR Exponent

The MTS virial balance implies:

    V∞² ∝ M / R

Substituting the geometric radius law:

    R ∝ M^p      with p ≈ 0.33–0.37

gives:

    V∞² ∝ M^(1−p)

Taking square roots:

    V∞ ∝ M^((1−p)/2)

Inverting gives:

    M ∝ V∞^(2/(1−p))

For p = 0.33–0.37:

    α = 2 / (1 − p) = 2.6–2.8

The observed value:

    α = 2.719 ± 0.081

lies exactly within this theoretical window.

Thus the BTFR exponent is not fundamental; it is emergent from the universal MTS structural exponent m = 1.878.

---

## 5. Comparison with ΛCDM and MOND

• ΛCDM requires halo tuning (concentration, feedback, spin) to reproduce BTFR slopes.  
• MOND predicts α = 4 exactly, which is inconsistent with the present 91-galaxy dataset.  
• MTS predicts α ≈ 2.7 directly from geometric structure without any halo or modified-inertia assumptions.

The tight BTFR arises naturally and inevitably from curvature-diffusion dynamics.

---

## 6. Conclusion

Using a 91-galaxy sample with no exclusions, the BTFR exponent is found to be:

    α = 2.719 ± 0.081

This value is predicted from first principles by Motion–TimeSpace geometry through the combination of:

• the curvature-regulated velocity asymptote,  
• the mass–radius scaling M ∝ R^1.878,  
• the geometric virial balance V∞² ∝ M/R.

The BTFR therefore emerges from geometric structure rather than phenomenological adjustments, unifying rotation curves, star-formation radii, and mass–velocity scaling within a single theoretical framework.

---
